From 7009c6bad8d2ad37dfd3594f114e6cb6ab2bcb5e Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Faisal Khan <mfkhan@sofi.org>
Date: Sun, 26 Apr 2026 01:58:59 -0700
Subject: [PATCH 11/12] fix(blog): use @starting-style for entrance to kill
 Firefox FOUC
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

The blog index entrance still flashed in Firefox after the previous
fix landed cleanly in Chrome. Root cause: `withViewTransitions()`
wraps Angular's route swap in `document.startViewTransition()`, but
that API is Chrome-only (Firefox keeps it behind
`dom.viewTransitions.enabled`). Chrome's snapshot crossfade hides the
one-frame gap between Angular inserting the new DOM and `animate.enter`
adding its `.fade-in` / `.enter-fade-up` class. Firefox falls back to
plain navigation, so the user sees:

  frame 1: new DOM rendered at default state (opacity 1, no transform)
  frame 2: animate.enter class lands, fill-mode `both` snaps element
           to from-state (opacity 0, translateY 12px)
  frames 3-N: animation interpolates back to the resting state

That snap from "fully visible" to "invisible" before the rise is the
flash described as jank — most visible on the first two cards because
they're highest in the viewport.

Replace `animate.enter` with CSS `@starting-style` for the blog index:

- `.blog-layout` and `.post-link` declare their resting state
  inline with a `transition` on opacity/transform; the per-card
  `transition-delay` reads the inline `--enter-delay` (i * 30ms) so
  the wave still staggers without any JS.
- A single `@starting-style { ... }` block declares the from-state
  (opacity: 0 + translateY for non-featured, opacity: 0 only for
  the featured card whose heavy 1600×900 cover would otherwise
  translate while it's still decoding).
- The browser applies `@starting-style` synchronously on the same
  insertion trigger animate.enter listens for, so the first paint is
  already the from-state. No FOUC in Firefox; Chrome's View
  Transition snapshot now also captures the from-state, so the
  crossfade is consistent across browsers.

Initial SSR loads remain unaffected — those elements are in the DOM
from frame zero with no insertion event, so @starting-style doesn't
trigger and the prerendered content shows immediately.

Reduced-motion contract is preserved by the global
`@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)` block in styles.css, which
squashes `transition-duration` (in addition to `animation-duration`)
to 0.01ms across all elements.

Browser support note: @starting-style is Baseline 2024 (Chrome 117+,
Firefox 129+, Safari 17.5+); all engines we ship to support it.

Made-with: Cursor
---
 src/app/features/blog/blog.component.css  | 57 +++++++++++++++++++----
 src/app/features/blog/blog.component.html | 37 ++++++++-------
 2 files changed, 68 insertions(+), 26 deletions(-)

diff --git a/src/app/features/blog/blog.component.css b/src/app/features/blog/blog.component.css
index dfaec971..1b4f1674 100644
--- a/src/app/features/blog/blog.component.css
+++ b/src/app/features/blog/blog.component.css
@@ -5,6 +5,14 @@
 .blog-layout {
   max-width: 900px;
   margin: 0 auto;
+  /*
+    Entrance ramp lives in the transition + @starting-style block at the
+    bottom of this file. We declare the resting state here so the
+    selector specificity matches what @starting-style overrides on
+    insertion.
+  */
+  opacity: 1;
+  transition: opacity var(--duration-base) var(--ease-decelerate);
 }
 
 .blog-header {
@@ -51,6 +59,17 @@
   text-decoration: none;
   color: inherit;
   display: block;
+  /*
+    Resting state for the entrance transition. The from-state lives in
+    the `@starting-style` block at the bottom of this file; the
+    transition-delay reads the inline `--enter-delay` set per-card in
+    the template (i * 30ms) so the wave staggers without any JS.
+  */
+  opacity: 1;
+  transform: translateY(0);
+  transition:
+    opacity var(--duration-base) var(--ease-decelerate) var(--enter-delay, 0ms),
+    transform var(--duration-base) var(--ease-decelerate) var(--enter-delay, 0ms);
 }
 
 /* The newest post is rendered as a hero card spanning the full grid width.
@@ -130,16 +149,36 @@
 }
 
 /*
-  The featured card carries `animate.enter="enter-fade-up"` along with
-  the rest of the grid for symmetry and a single class hook, but its
-  cover image is heavy (1600×900 webp, async-decoded) and translating
-  it 12px while it's still resolving reads as jank. Override the
-  `animation-name` on the enter class so the featured card rides the
-  same timing/delay/easing but only ramps opacity. Non-featured cards
-  keep the original rise.
+  Entrance from-state, applied synchronously on element insertion via
+  CSS `@starting-style`. Using @starting-style here (instead of the
+  `animate.enter` directive we use elsewhere) avoids a Firefox-specific
+  flash on client-side route navigation: animate.enter adds its class
+  one frame after insertion, which Chrome's View Transitions snapshot
+  crossfade hides but Firefox (which doesn't yet support the View
+  Transitions API and falls back to plain nav) reveals as a one-frame
+  flash of fully-rendered content snapping to opacity:0 before the
+  rise. The browser applies @starting-style on the same insertion
+  trigger but synchronously, so the first paint is already the
+  from-state and the transition runs cleanly in both browsers.
+
+  Featured card uses opacity-only — translating the heavy cover image
+  while it's still decoding looks jank, so the from-state explicitly
+  pins transform to none.
 */
-.post-link--featured.enter-fade-up {
-  animation-name: simple-fade-in;
+@starting-style {
+  .blog-layout {
+    opacity: 0;
+  }
+
+  .post-link {
+    opacity: 0;
+    transform: translateY(12px);
+  }
+
+  .post-link--featured {
+    opacity: 0;
+    transform: none;
+  }
 }
 
 .post-link--featured .post-card-body {
